{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"799a335c-4039-4f95-8ffa-6bc09b168b1e","content":"Add a `.vscode/mcp.json` file to your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- `type: \"stdio\"` means Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- `command`/`args` launch your server via `dotnet run`.\n- If you publish a self-contained executable instead, point `command` directly at the binary.\n\nAfter adding this file, restart VS Code or reload the window. Copilot agent mode will automatically discover and connect to your MCP server.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"64befc42-2b10-4166-85b8-2a3e4137deb0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to configure `mcp.json` to use their C# MCP server with GitHub Copilot in VS Code agent mode. Let me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge of VS Code MCP configuration.","outputTokens":265,"requestId":"201F:229C6C:16106E5:18BDBCD:6A0521BC"},"id":"11293738-2128-4171-a556-81ab4290756b","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:13:39.007Z","parentId":"ba13bf6c-7b1a-471c-82d3-a85f84f3e37c"}
